ğŸ§  What is OOP? (Very Important)

Object-Oriented Programming is a programming style where we:

Model real-world things

Using objects

That interact with each other

ğŸ‘‰ Java is 100% object-oriented (except primitives).

Real world example:

Car

Bank Account

Student

Order

User

Each has:

Data (state)

Actions (behavior)

ğŸ”¹ 1. Object
ğŸ“Œ Definition

An object is a real-world entity that:

Has state

Has behavior

Has identity

ğŸ‘‰ In Java, everything revolves around objects.

ğŸ“Œ Example (Real World)

Student Object

State â†’ name, rollNo, marks

Behavior â†’ study(), giveExam()

ğŸ“Œ Example (Java Code)
Student s1 = new Student();


s1 is an object of class Student.

ğŸ§  Key Points (Write this in notes)

Object is a runtime entity

Created using new keyword

Occupies memory (heap)

Multiple objects can be created from the same class

ğŸ”¹ 2. Class
ğŸ“Œ Definition

A class is a blueprint/template used to create objects.

ğŸ‘‰ Class does NOT occupy memory
ğŸ‘‰ Objects DO occupy memory

ğŸ“Œ Real World Analogy

Class = Blueprint of a house

Object = Actual house built from blueprint

ğŸ“Œ Example (Java Code)
class Student {
    String name;
    int rollNo;

    void study() {
        System.out.println("Student is studying");
    }
}

ğŸ”¹ 3. State (Instance Variables)
ğŸ“Œ Definition

State represents the data of an object.

ğŸ‘‰ Stored using variables

ğŸ“Œ Example
class Car {
    String brand;
    int speed;
}

ğŸ”¹ 4. Behavior (Methods)
ğŸ“Œ Definition

Behavior defines what an object can do.

ğŸ‘‰ Implemented using methods

ğŸ“Œ Example
class BankAccount {
    int balance;

    void deposit(int amount) {
        balance += amount;
    }

    void withdraw(int amount) {
        balance -= amount;
    }
}


âœ… Why new is an operator, not a keyword

In Java:

Keyword â†’ reserved word used only for syntax/structure
Examples: class, int, if, return

Operator â†’ performs an action on operands and returns a result
Examples: +, =, instanceof, new